The **Outback Bowl** is an annual [college football](/wiki/College_football
"College football") [bowl game](/wiki/Bowl_game "Bowl game") played at
[Raymond James Stadium](/wiki/Raymond_James_Stadium "Raymond James Stadium")
in [Tampa, Florida](/wiki/Tampa,_Florida "Tampa, Florida"), usually on [New
Years Day](/wiki/New_Years_Day "New Years Day"). The event was originally
called the **Hall of Fame Bowl** from 1986 to 1994 until being renamed in 1995
for its new title sponsor, [Outback Steakhouse](/wiki/Outback_Steakhouse
"Outback Steakhouse"). It is organized by the Tampa Bay Bowl Association under
Jim McVay, who has been the president/CEO since 1988.

## History[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Outback_Bowl&action=edit&section=1 "Edit
section: History")]

### Cigar Bowl[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Outback_Bowl&action=edit&section=2
"Edit section: Cigar Bowl")]

The Outback Bowl was not Tampa's first bowl game; the [Cigar
Bowl](/wiki/Cigar_Bowl "Cigar Bowl") was played at old [Phillips
Field](/wiki/Sports_in_the_Tampa_Bay_Area#Phillips_Field "Sports in the Tampa
Bay Area") near downtown from 1947 to 1954. However, the earlier event matched
small college teams, so the Outback / Hall of Fame Bowl is the first major
bowl game to be played in the area.

### Hall of Fame
Bowl[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Outback_Bowl&action=edit&section=3 "Edit
section: Hall of Fame Bowl")]

The [Hall of Fame Classic](/wiki/All-American_Bowl "All-American Bowl") was
held at [Legion Field](/wiki/Legion_Field "Legion Field") in [Birmingham,
Alabama](/wiki/Birmingham,_Alabama "Birmingham, Alabama") from 1977 to 1985.
In the spring of 1986, the [National Football
Foundation](/wiki/National_Football_Foundation "National Football Foundation")
and [College Football Hall of Fame](/wiki/College_Football_Hall_of_Fame
"College Football Hall of Fame") decided to discontinue their association with
the bowl and realign with a new bowl game to be played in [Tampa
Stadium](/wiki/Tampa_Stadium "Tampa Stadium") which would inherit the Hall of
Fame Bowl name. Initially, the Hall of Fame Bowl did not have agreements with
any conferences, so it usually matched a school from either the [Southeastern
Conference](/wiki/Southeastern_Conference "Southeastern Conference") or the
[Atlantic Coast Conference](/wiki/Atlantic_Coast_Conference "Atlantic Coast
Conference") against a team from another region of the country.

### Outback Bowl[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Outback_Bowl&action=edit&section=4
"Edit section: Outback Bowl")]

[Outback Steakhouse](/wiki/Outback_Steakhouse "Outback Steakhouse") became the
game's title sponsor in 1995. At the same time, the newly renamed Outback Bowl
signed agreements with the Southeastern Conference and the [Big Ten
Conference](/wiki/Big_Ten_Conference "Big Ten Conference"), creating an annual
inter-sectional matchup that has continued ever since.

In 1999, the Outback Bowl moved from Tampa Stadium into [Raymond James
Stadium](/wiki/Raymond_James_Stadium "Raymond James Stadium"), which had
recently been built adjacent to the old stadium.

## The game[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Outback_Bowl&action=edit&section=5 "Edit
section: The game")]

The Outback Bowl is played on [New Year's Day](/wiki/New_Year%27s_Day "New
Year's Day") unless January 1 falls on a Sunday, in which case it is moved to
the following Monday. It is usually the first game to start on a day which is
traditionally full of college bowl games, and has kicked off as early as 11AM.
[ESPN](/wiki/ESPN "ESPN") has had television rights to the game since 1993.
Under an extension of those rights signed in 2010, ESPN broadcasts the game on
either [ABC](/wiki/ESPN_on_ABC "ESPN on ABC"), ESPN, or [ESPN2](/wiki/ESPN2
"ESPN2"), in conjunction with the [Citrus Bowl](/wiki/Citrus_Bowl "Citrus
Bowl") and the [New Year's
Six](/wiki/College_Football_Playoff_New_Year%27s_Six "College Football Playoff
New Year's Six") bowl games.[3] Before 1993, the Hall of Fame Bowl aired on
[NBC](/wiki/NBC_Sports "NBC Sports").

Upon signing agreements with the SEC and Big 10 in 1995, the Outback Bowl had
the third pick of teams from each conference after the [Bowl Championship
Series](/wiki/Bowl_Championship_Series "Bowl Championship Series") teams were
placed. Since 2014, both the SEC and Big 10 have worked with a group of
several bowl games, including the Outback Bowl, to place their bowl-eligible
teams after the [College Football Playoff](/wiki/College_Football_Playoff
"College Football Playoff") and associated bowls have made their
selections.[4][5]

As of 2017, the Outback Bowl payout was $3.5 million for each team.
